    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-10-09T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-10-09T07:00:00-05:00" n="293"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d293">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/11687</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Greece</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Chabot</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Athens</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-10-09T14:00:00+02:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 9, 1918, 2 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received October 10, 4.50 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>578. In regard to Legation’s 576, October 7 [<hi rend="italic">6</hi>], 2
                        a.m.<note n="1" xml:id="d293fn1">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_341">p. 341</ref>.</note>
                    British Minister just called at Legation to say that he has had a reply from
                        <persName corresp="#p_LGD1">Lloyd George</persName>, who is at Paris, that
                    British Government cannot consider any negotiations with those not actually the
                    Turkish Government. British Minister communicating this reply to [Carabiber] for
                    Rahmi evidently, and delegates are leaving immediately.</p>
                <p>Note to British Minister added: If proposed new government were to become the
                    actual Turkish Government, then negotiations would <pb facs="0445" n="353"
                        xml:id="pg_353"/> be acceptable. If any armistice is desired, <persName
                        corresp="#p_AGEHH1">General Allenby</persName> should be approached. Terms
                    suggested are quite out of the question.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chabot</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
